library(dplyr)
library(tidyverse)

# Create a new variable "avgsale"
df <- dataset %>%
  mutate(avgsale = totsale / totord)

# Add a new variable "promotion_number" based on row number
df <- df %>%
  mutate(promotion_number = row_number())

# Calculate expected revenue per promotional contact for each promotion
df <- df %>%
  mutate(avg_sale_per_contact = avgsale / rowSums(select(contactdf, starts_with("crcpr"))))

# Filter out non-finite values
df_filtered <- df %>%
  filter(!is.na(avg_sale_per_contact) & is.finite(avg_sale_per_contact))

# Visualize expected revenue per promotional contact
ggplot(df_filtered, aes(x = promotion_number, y = avg_sale_per_contact)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm") +
  xlab("Lifetime Number of Promotional Contacts (crcpr)") +
  ylab("Average Sales per Order (avgsale)")
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

# Calculate the cumulative sum of unique promotional contacts for each promotion
df <- df %>%
  mutate(cumulative_unique_contacts = apply(select(contactdf, starts_with("crcpr")), 1, function(x) length(unique(x))))

# Filter out non-finite values
df_filtered <- df %>%
  filter(!is.na(avg_sale_per_contact) & is.finite(avg_sale_per_contact))

# Visualize expected revenue per promotional contact
ggplot(df_filtered, aes(x = cumulative_unique_contacts, y = avg_sale_per_contact)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm") +
  xlab("Cumulative Unique Lifetime Number of Promotional Contacts (crcpr)") +
  ylab("Average Sales per Order (avgsale)")
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

# Fit the linear model
lm_model <- lm(avg_sale_per_contact ~ cumulative_unique_contacts, data = df_filtered)

# Extract the slope from the model summary
slope <- coef(lm_model)[2]

# Print the slope
print(paste("Slope of the line:", slope))
## [1] "Slope of the line: -0.901013909121508"
# Fit a linear regression model
model <- lm(avg_sale_per_contact ~ cumulative_unique_contacts, data = df_filtered)
summary(model)

##Lasso and Ridge Regression Model

# Load required libraries
library(glmnet)
library(caret)

# Assuming your dataset is stored in a data frame called 'data'
# Create a matrix of independent variables (promotional contacts)
X <- as.matrix(dataset[, c("crcpr01", "crcpr10", "crcpr17", "crcpr21", "crcpr24", "crcpr35", 
                        "crcpr50", "crcpr60", "crcpr65", "crcpr72", "crcpr85", "crcpr93")])

# Create a vector of the dependent variable (sales per order)
Y <- dataset$totord / dataset$totsale

# Check if Y has constant values or missing values
if (length(unique(Y)) == 1) {
  stop("The dependent variable Y has constant values. Please check your data.")
}

if (anyNA(Y)) {
  stop("The dependent variable Y contains missing values. Please handle missing values in Y.")
}

# Take a random sample of the data
set.seed(123)  # For reproducibility
sample_indices <- sample(1:nrow(dataset), size = 10000, replace = FALSE)
X <- X[sample_indices, ]
Y <- Y[sample_indices]

# Split the data into training and testing sets
train_indices <- createDataPartition(Y, p = 0.7, list = FALSE)
train_X <- X[train_indices, ]
train_Y <- Y[train_indices]
test_X <- X[-train_indices, ]
test_Y <- Y[-train_indices]

# Standardize the independent variables
train_X <- scale(train_X)
test_X <- scale(test_X)

# Fit lasso regression model
lasso_model <- cv.glmnet(x = train_X, y = train_Y, alpha = 1)  # alpha = 1 for lasso
lambda_min <- lasso_model$lambda.min  # Optimal lambda value

# Fit ridge regression model
ridge_model <- cv.glmnet(x = train_X, y = train_Y, alpha = 0)  # alpha = 0 for ridge

# Predict on the testing set using the lasso model
lasso_preds <- predict(lasso_model, newx = test_X, s = lambda_min)

# Predict on the testing set using the ridge model
ridge_preds <- predict(ridge_model, newx = test_X, s = "lambda.min")

# Calculate evaluation metrics
lasso_mse <- mean((test_Y - lasso_preds)^2)
ridge_mse <- mean((test_Y - ridge_preds)^2)

# Print the evaluation metrics
cat("Lasso MSE:", lasso_mse, "\n")
## Lasso MSE: 0.02350558
cat("Ridge MSE:", ridge_mse, "\n")
## Ridge MSE: 0.02350401
lasso_coef <- coef(lasso_model, s = lambda_min)

# Determine the non-zero coefficients
non_zero_coef <- which(lasso_coef != 0)

# Select the corresponding variables/features
selected_vars <- colnames(train_X)[non_zero_coef]

# Interpret the coefficients
lasso_coef_non_zero <- lasso_coef[non_zero_coef]
coef_interpretation <- data.frame(Variable = selected_vars, Coefficient = lasso_coef_non_zero)

# Print the coefficient interpretation
print(coef_interpretation)

# Extract coefficients from Lasso model
lasso_coefs <- coef(lasso_model)
nonzero_coefs <- lasso_coefs[-1, lambda_min != 0]  # Exclude intercept and select non-zero coefficients

# Count the number of non-zero coefficients (optimal number of promotional contacts)
optimal_num_contacts <- length(nonzero_coefs)

# Print the optimal number of promotional contacts
cat("Optimal number of promotional contacts:", optimal_num_contacts, "\n")
## Optimal number of promotional contacts: 12
# Calculate the average number of promotions a customer receives during their lifetime
avg_num_promotions <- mean(dataset$totord)

# Calculate the optimal number of promotional contacts for a single promotion
optimal_contacts_per_promotion <- optimal_num_contacts / avg_num_promotions

# Print the optimal number of promotional contacts per promotion
cat("Optimal number of promotional contacts per promotion:", optimal_contacts_per_promotion, "\n")
